{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412818"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501595"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1768"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261079"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:40:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T08:44:36+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":4,"questionsAnswered":3,"marksTotal":4,"marksAttainable":3,"marksAttempted":3,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:39+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1768"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.59,0.36,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111841"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1768"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1768"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93911"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"916"},{"type":"tags","id":"2089"},{"type":"tags","id":"2309"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10686"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40216"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111841"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of worsening and persistent right-sided hearing loss, tinnitus, and dizziness. She reports difficulty hearing out of her right ear, particularly when on the telephone, that is gradually worsening, with an associated sensation of fullness in the ear. She describes unsteadiness when walking and the room spinning around her. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Rinne\u0027s test is positive bilaterally, and Weber\u0027s test lateralises to the left. A change in head position does not elicit her symptoms. Cranial nerve examination reveals mild nystagmus; otherwise, all other cranial nerve functions are intact and normal. Otoscopic examination reveals minimal wax bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Meniere\u0027s disease","Acoustic neuroma","Otosclerosis","Vestibular migraine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacoustic neuroma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is a benign tumour of the vestibulocochlear nerve (eighth cranial nerve). The key features supporting this diagnosis are the gradual onset of unilateral sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, vertigo, and gait imbalance over six months. The sensorineural nature of the hearing loss is evidenced by a positive Rinne\u0027s test bilaterally and Weber\u0027s test lateralising to the unaffected (left) ear. The sensation of aural fullness and mild nystagmus on examination further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune demyelinating disease of the central nervous system that can present with a wide range of neurological symptoms. However, pure unilateral sensorineural hearing loss is less characteristic of multiple sclerosis, and the gradual onset over six months would be unusual for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms, including episodic vertigo, sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, and aural fullness. However, the vertigo in Meniere\u0027s disease is typically more severe, associated with nausea and vomiting, and occurs in discrete episodes lasting over 20 minutes. The gradual progression of symptoms in this case is more consistent with acoustic neuroma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtosclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes bilateral conductive hearing loss due to abnormal bone growth in the middle ear, usually affecting the stapes bone. The sensorineural hearing loss and unilateral nature of the symptoms in this case make otosclerosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular migraine\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by recurrent episodes of vertigo, imbalance, and headache. The absence of headache and the gradual, progressive nature of the symptoms make vestibular migraine an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the presentation of gradually worsening unilateral sensorineural hearing loss, tinnitus, vertigo, and gait imbalance, an acoustic neuroma is the most likely diagnosis. Further investigation with magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the internal auditory canals would be appropriate to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The main presentation of acoustic neuroma is unilateral sensorineural hearing loss, as well as tinnitus, vertigo, gait imbalance and aural fullness.","Acoustic neuroma is a benign tumour of the vestibulocochlear nerve that typically presents with gradual onset of unilateral hearing loss and balance disturbances."],"references":["Dommaraju S, Perera E. An approach to vertigo in general practice. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2016;45:190-4. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2016/april/an-approach-to-vertigo-in-general-practice","Lewis S, Chowdhury E, Stockdale D, Kennedy V; Guideline Committee. Assessment and management of tinnitus: summary of NICE guidance. BMJ. 2020 Mar 31;368:m976. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32234748/","Greene J, Al-Dhahir MA. Acoustic Neuroma. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470177/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93911"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1768"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":